<p>

In the earliest days of cartoons, voice actors were seldom credited for their work. A little more than a decade ago, even the <union wordnetid="108233056" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../218/129218.xml">
Screen Actors Guild</link></union>
 did not consider voice actors to be real actors, and the only voice actor known to the general public was <actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../748/44748.xml">
Mel Blanc</link></actor>
. Now, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../324/324.xml">
Oscar</link>-winning celebrities clamor to guest star on animated television shows and features. </p>
<p>

Despite the crushing turnouts at signings for shows such as <series wordnetid="108457976" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../945/1945.xml">
